1. Income

  1. Describe in detail the features you observe in the box plots below, plotted with data from the ex0525 data set, Sleuth3 page. (see page 29 in Graphical Data Analysis in R for a list of features to concentrate on, and the numbered list on the bottom of page 43 for an example of how to describe features of a graph in words.) [5 points]
# install.packages("Sleuth3")
library(Sleuth3)
library(tidyverse)
# convert Educ from an integer to a factor, and make "<12" the first factor level 
mydata <- ex0525 %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(Educ = forcats::fct_relevel(Educ, "<12"))
ggplot(mydata, aes(Educ, Income2005)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()   # for horizontal boxplots

  • Income and the years of education have a positive relationship. As the years of education increase so does income. Variability in income increases as education goes up and the general mean is higher. Looking at 16>, there’s a crazy outlier with $600,000 +. There’s simply a trend of people earning more if they spend more time in school.
  1. Plot a histogram of the Income2005 variable in the data set referenced in part a). [3 points]
ggplot(ex0525, aes(x=Income2005)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=60)

  1. Use +facet_wrap(~Educ) to facet the histogram on education level. [3 points]
ggplot(ex0525, aes(Income2005)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=60) +
  facet_wrap(~Educ)

  1. What do you learn from the histograms that wasn’t apparent in the box plots from question 1? [3 points]
  • It’s now way easier to see the distribution and where the data is concentrated. We could now see that there are more people who only completed 12 years of school. There’s an inverse relationship between number of participants and their years of education. As the years of education increase the number of people participating goes down.

2. Respiratory Rates

  1. Plot right closed and right open histograms for each of the two variables in the ex0824 data set in the Sleuth3 package using default binwidths and breaks. (4 histograms in total). [4 points]
hist(ex0824$Age, left=TRUE, right=FALSE)

hist(ex0824$Age, left=FALSE, right=TRUE)

hist(ex0824$Rate, left=TRUE, right=FALSE)

hist(ex0824$Rate, left=FALSE, right=TRUE)

  1. For which variable, Age or Rate, do the two versions differ more? Why? [3 points]

  • The “Rate” histogram differs more, because the data is continuous as opposed to “Age” that’s discrete. If right is “TRUE”, which it is by default, the left is open and the right is closed eg (a, b] and vice versa if right is “FALSE”, eg [a,b).

  • What this means for continuous data, if right=“TRUE”, is when a bin is (4, 8] and a continuous number 8.4 appears, it’ll go into that bin. If a bin is [4,8) and a 8.4 appears, it’ll go into the next bin. When graphing continuous data choosing which side you want to focus makes a difference.

types limit open/closed
(4, 8) 4 < x < 8 left-open, right-open
[4, 8) 4 ≤ x < 8 left-closed, right-open
(4, 8] 4 < x ≤ 8 left-open, right-closed
(4, 8] 4 ≤ x ≤ 8 left-closed, right-closed
  1. Redraw the Age histograms with different parameters so that the right closed and right open versions are identical. [3 points]
hist(ex0824$Age, breaks=2, left=TRUE, right=FALSE)

hist(ex0824$Age, breaks=2, left=FALSE, right=TRUE)

3. Movie budgets

Are there rounding patterns in the budget variable of the movies in the ggplot2movies package? If so, what are the patterns? (Note: according to the textbook this data set is in the ggplot2 package, but it has since been moved to a separate package.) Support your conclusions with graphical evidence. You are encouraged to break the variable down into different budget ranges and consider them separately. [8 points]

# install.packages("ggplot2movies")
library(ggplot2movies)
m <- ggplot2movies::movies
summary(m$budget)
     Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max.      NA's 
        0    250000   3000000  13412513  15000000 200000000     53573 
m$budget_group = cut(m$budget, c(0,100000,1000000, 10000000, 100000000, 1000000000))
levels(m$budget_group) = c("1K","1M","10M", "100M", "1B")
library(lattice)
histogram(m$budget_group)

summary(m$budget_group)
   1K    1M   10M  100M    1B  NA's 
  976  1030  1556  1562    59 53605
  • 53605 out of 58,788 movies have “N/A” for their budget. That leaves 5,183 with a recorded budget. Outside of the handful of movies that hit 1 billion in their budget, the rest of the movies don’t appear to differ much in their budget. I would not be surprised if there are rounding errors.

4. Finches

  1. Plot separate density histograms of the beak depth of the finches in case0201 from the Sleuth3 package, with density curves overlaid as on page 34 of the textbook. (However, do this by facetting on Year rather than using grid.arrange). [3 points]
ggplot(case0201, aes(Depth)) +
  geom_density() +
  scale_fill_manual() +
  scale_x_continuous() +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.6, aes(y=..count../80/.1), binwidth=.1) +
  facet_grid(Year~.)

  1. Plot both density curves on the same graph to facilitate comparison. Make 1976 yellow and 1978 blue. Use alpha blending so the fills are transparent. [3 points]
case0201$Year <- factor(case0201$Year, labels = c('1976', '1978'))
qplot(Depth, data=case0201, geom='density', alpha=I(.3), fill=Year) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("yellow","blue"))

# # converting Year into a factor
# case0201$Year <- factor(case0201$Year, labels = c('1976', '1978'))
# ggplot(case0201, aes(x=Depth, fill=Year)) +
#   geom_density(alpha=.3) +
#   scale_fill_manual(values = c("yellow","blue"))
  1. Based on your graphs in parts a) and b), describe how the distributions differ by year. [3 points]
  • There’s an obvious shift in the population mean from 1976 to 1978. The 1978 distribution is skewing further right and shows a clear change in the population of birds towards the ones with larger beaks.
  1. What is the cause of the difference according to the information in the help file? [3 points]
  • The cause in the difference is drought. From 1976 to 1978 the common seeds that finches lived off of disappeared. The only seeds that survived the drought required finches to have bigger and stronger beaks; the ones that did not, couldn’t reproduce.

5. Salary

Is the Salary variable in the case0101 of Sleuth3 normally distributed? Use two different graphical methods to provide evidence. [6 points] * case0101 {Sleuth3} is data on “Motivation and Creativity”. There’s no variable, Salary. Instead, I’ll see if Score, a variable in the data set is normally distributed.

summary(case0101$Score)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
   5.00   14.90   18.70   17.86   21.25   29.70 
qqnorm(case0101$Score); qqline(case0101$Score, col = 2)

plot(density(case0101$Score))

  • The Score variable is normally distributed. The mean and mode are very close together. The linear model shows that the data has a positive relationship. For the most part, the density plot shows evenness on both sides.
